Rabies, Italy
-------------
Information received on (and dated) 2 Feb 2010 from Prof Dr Romano
Marabelli, [Head, Department of Veterinary Pubic Health, Nutrition
and Food Safety, Ministry of Labor, Health and Social Policies], Rome, Italy

Summary
Report type: follow-up report no. 34
Start date: 10 Oct 2008
Date of 1st confirmation of the event: 17 Oct 2008
Date submitted to OIE: 2 Feb 2010
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 1995
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: Rabies virus
Serotype: RABV
Nature of diagnosis: suspicion, laboratory (advanced), necropsy
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country

[Details of each of the 17 cases are to be viewed in the full report,
omitted here].

Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 17
Total animals affected
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Wild species / - / 16 / 12 / 4 / 0
Cats / - / 1 / 1 / 0 / 0

Epidemiological comments
Starting from October 2008, the rabies cases detected are 119 (105
foxes, 5 badgers, 3 roes, 3 dogs, 1 beech marten, 1 cat, and 1
donkey) distributed in the following regions: Friuli-Venezia, Giulia
(Udine, Pordenone, and Trieste provinces), and Veneto (Belluno province).
New vaccination campaigns have been implemented as follows:
1. At the beginning of December 2009 (100 000 additional baits for
foxes, manual distribution) all over the territory of Friuli-Venezia
Giulia, where the previous campaigns were put in place (about 4500 sq
km) [approx. 1700 sq mi];
2. Starting on 28 Dec 2009 (300 000 baits for foxes, air distribution
with helicopters) and continuing on January 2010 (manual
distribution) covering the following territories (about 17 500 sq km)
[approx 6800 sq mi], avoiding areas where baits would be exposed to
freezing temperatures:
- Veneto region: Belluno, Treviso, and Vicenza provinces and part of
Padova, Venezia, and Verona provinces;
- part of Bolzano province;
- part of Trento province.

Control measures
Measures applied
Control of wildlife reservoirs
Vaccination in response to the outbreak(s)
Administrative division / Species / Total Vaccinated / Details
Friuli-Venezia Giulia / wild species / 222 000 / baits for foxes -
modified-live vaccine Rabigen SAG2-Virbac
Veneto / wild species / 300 000 / baits for foxes - modified-live
vaccine SAD B 19-IDT Biologika
No treatment of affected animals

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Italy had been classified as rabies-free since 1997. In October
2008, 2 foxes were diagnosed with rabies in the Province of Udine,
northeast Italy. One case of human exposure caused by a bite from one
of the foxes occurred and was properly treated. Since then, the
disease has spread within the regional fox population, eventually
leading to the need for the application of wildlife oral vaccination
described above.

For background, see
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/images/dynamic/EE/V13N45/art19033.pdf> and
<http://www.hpa.org.uk/web/HPAweb&HPAwebStandard/HPAweb_C/1224745740644>.
- Mod.AS]
